<subSubSection id="A9672C132D4A3C696D7472F635BA11C2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="33FC87094F48B821254C15D4D1E40065" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="894DE43DE21F4426EB55F44C18104398" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Despite several investigations in Mt. Tianmen and the surrounding areas (96 km2), two populations with nearly 500 individuals each (total &lt;1000) of 
<taxonomicName id="342757A4DD32ED4DAD23F5AF77FC603C" authorityName="Jia X. Li" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gentianaceae" genus="Swertia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Swertia hongquanii" order="Gentianales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hongquanii">
<emphasis id="3A00EB50814824080B6CB15A153F4E74" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Swertia hongquanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found only at the type locality (towering summit terrace with an area of 2 km2). Presently, a tourist plank walkway passes through this location and its habitat could be easily disturbed or destroyed. According to the 
<bibRefCitation id="9C8547FD4838DE9630501CA329998712" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Acta Phytotaxonomica Sinica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B10" refString="IUCN, 2017. Guidelines for using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the standards and petitions subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for using the IUCN red list categories and criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the standards and petitions subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN (2017)</bibRefCitation>
criterion D thresholds (mature individuals &lt;1000, AOO &lt;20 km2), the new species could be assessed as VU. However, it grows in the upper part of steep limestone mountains surrounded by cliffs, which previously made it impossible to be encountered until a plank walkway was built across the cliff face for tourists. With limited fieldwork executed at present, it is possible that more populations could be found in similar habitats of the Wuling mountain areas. Therefore, we consider the species DD (Data Deficient).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
